description.p:
Available microwave chemical experiments are mainly carried out in rectangular waveguide or resonant-cavity formed by the rectangular waveguide, which are still limited in rectangular waveguide; obstacles for producing ethene from methane (natural gas) by microwave chemical method comprises:
(1) Small resonant-cavity volume for microwave chemical reaction;
(2) Small flow rate of feed gas methane (natural gas);
(3) Ethene single-pass yield less than 40%.

The method for producing ethene from natural gas by using the resonant cavity-type groove guide microwave chemical plant comprises:
(1) adopting a large-size resonant cavity-type groove guide microwave chemical plant with working frequency within 0.3-22GHz, wherein the microwave source can adopt continuous wave or pulsed wave;
(2) allowing the resonant cavity-type groove guide microwave chemical plant to be in resonant state, and allowing the reactor to be in vacuum state;
(3) selecting hydrogen as auxiliary gas;
(4) regulating pressures of feed natural gas and auxiliary hydrogen gas to 1-20 atm, respectively introducing them into the reactor via different flow meters for metering flow rates of the different gases;
(5) adopting feed natural gas and auxiliary hydrogen gas flow rate ratio, i.e. natural gas: hydrogen gas, at 50:1-1:20;
(6) mixing the feed natural gas and the auxiliary hydrogen gas in a gas mixture cabinet, and introducing into quartz reactor of the resonant cavity-type groove guide microwave chemical plant via the feed gas inlet tube and the upper end cover;
(7) regulating the total pressure of the mixed gas in the quartz reactor to 1x10-4 - 20 atm, and making the total pressure of the mixed gas in the quartz reactor slightly lower than the pressure of the feed natural gas and the auxiliary hydrogen gas;
(8) switching on the microwave source power supply, regulating microwave output power to several dozen watts to several hundred kilowatts according to auxiliary gas type, flow rate ratio, and gas mixture pressure, and allowing the gas mixture in the quartz reaction tube to discharge so as to generate microwave plasma, wherein discharge condition can be learned from the Langmuir probe and the cutoff waveguide;
(9) then fine tuning microwave output power to obtain required product, wherein the required product ethene in liquid state can be collected in the condensation trap.

Now the aforementioned parts are assembled according to figure 2 and 1 to give the resonant cavity-type recess waveguide microwave chemical plant, the assembly comprises:
(1) removing machine oil on each parts, and cleaning;
(2) assembling each parts of the short-circuiting plunger 3 including the first short-circuiting plunger metal plate 31, the second short-circuiting plunger metal plate 32, the third short-circuiting plunger metal plate 33, the first round insulation gasket 34, the second round insulation gasket 35, the hollow round tube 36, and the metal round rod 37 according to figure 2 into an assembly;
(3) arranging the left metal flat plate 11, the right metal flat plate 12, the wedge-shaped matched load 13, the insulation strips 14, and the short-circuiting plunger 4 of the recess waveguide 1 according to figure 2, fixing with screw, and reserving corresponding holes on the insulation strips for passing the round tubular chemical reactor;
(4) connecting the first mode transducer 21 and the second mode transducer 23, connecting the other end of the second mode transducer 23 with the recess waveguide, fixing the other end of the first mode transducer 21 with the rectangular waveguide flange 22, and connecting the other end of the rectangular waveguide flange 22 with the coupling diaphragm 24;
(5) fixing the metal flat plate 39 with the sleeve 38 on the other end of the groove guide 1 via screws, making the hollow round tube 36 of the short-circuiting plunger 3 pass the sleeve 38 on the metal flat plate 39 and connect with the mechanical adjustment mechanism, and making the short-circuiting plunger 3 movable in the recess groove guide 1 in parallel without any obstacle;
(6) disposing the exciter 44 into the reactor 41;
(7) according to figure 2, allowing the reactor 41 to pass one wing of the groove guide 1 and extend out of the groove guide from the other wing of the groove guide 1, fitting the vacuum-proof upper end cover 42 on one end of the reactor 41, and connecting the feed gas inlet tube 46 with the upper end cover 42; fitting the vacuum-proof lower end cover 43 on the other end of the reactor 41, and connecting the lower end cover with the product gas outlet tube 47;
(8) according to figure 1, connecting the feed gas inlet tube 46 on the upper end cover 42 with the natural gas pipeline (or methane cylinder) via a flow meter, and connecting the product gas outlet tube 47 on the lower end cover 43 with the vacuum pump via the condensation trap;
(9) according to figure 2, inserting Langmuir Probe 45 via hole reserved on the upper end cover 42 to desirable position, and fixing on the upper end cover 42 while making connection part airtight;
(10) according to figure 2, connecting the cutoff waveguide 15 on outer side of the observation hole of the left metal flat plate 11 of the recess waveguide;
(11) connecting the microwave source with the coupling diaphragm 24 via the circulator and directional coupler, connecting power indicators on two auxiliary arms of the directional coupler, and regulating the short-circuiting plunger to make the resonant cavity in resonant state;

claim.claim-text:
Ein Verfahren zur Herstellung von Ethen aus Naturgas unter Einsatz der chemischen Hohlraumresonatoranlage mit Schlitzwellenleitermikrowelle nach Anspruch 1, dadurch gekennzeichnet, dass das Verfahren zur Herstellung von Ethen aus Naturgas umfasst:
(1) Verwenden einer chemischen Hohlraumresonatoranlage mit Schlitzwellenleitermikrowelle mit einer Arbeitsfrequenz innerhalb von 0,3-22 GHz, wobei die Mikrowellenquelle den Dauerstrichbetrieb oder den Impulsbetrieb wählen kann;
(2) Ermöglichen, dass sich die chemische Hohlraumresonatoranlage mit Schlitzwellenleitermikrowelle im Resonanzzustand befindet und Ermöglichen, dass sich der Reaktor im Vakuumzustand befindet;
(3) Auswählen von Wasserstoffgas als Hilfsgas;
(4) Einstellen der Drücke von Speisenaturgas und Hilfswasserstoffgas auf 1-20 atm bzw. Einleiten der Gase in den Reaktor über unterschiedliche Durchflussmesser zum Messen der Strömungsgeschwindigkeiten der unterschiedlichen Gase;
(5) Wählen eines Verhältnisses der Strömungsgeschwindigkeiten von Speisenaturgas und Hilfswasserstoffgas, d.h., Naturgas:Wasserstoffgas, von 50:1-1:20;
(6) Mischen des Speisenaturgases und des Hilfswasserstoffgases in einer Gasgemischkammer und Einleiten in den Quarzreaktor (41) der chemischen Hohlraumresonatoranlage mit Schlitzwellenleitermikrowelle über das Speisegaseinlassrohr (46) und die obere Endabdeckung (42);
(7) Einstellen des Gesamtdrucks des Gasgemisches im Quarzreaktor (41) auf 1x10-4 - 20 atm und Einstellen des Gesamtdrucks des Gasgemisches im Quarzreaktor (41) auf einen Wert, der geringfügig unter dem des Drucks des Speisenaturgases und des Hilfswasserstoffgases liegt;
(8) Einschalten der Stromversorgung der Mikrowellenquelle, Einstellen der Mikrowellenausgangsleistung auf mehrere Dutzend Watt bis mehrere Hundert Kilowatt je nach Hilfsgastyp, Verhältnis der Strömungsgeschwindigkeiten und Gasgemischdruck, und Ermöglichen, dass sich das Gasgemisch im Quarzreaktor (41) entlädt, um Mikrowellenplasma zu erzeugen, wobei die Entladebedingung aus der Langmuir-Sonde (44) und dem Wellenleiter mit herabgesetzter kritischer Frequenz entnommen werden kann;
(9) anschließendes Feineinstellen der Mikrowellenausgangsleistung, um das gewünschte Produkt zu gewinnen, wobei das gewünschte Produkt Ethen im flüssigen Zustand in der Kühlfalle aufgefangen werden kann.

A method for producing ethene from natural gas by using the resonant cavity-type groove guide microwave chemical plant as claimed in claim 1, characterized in that the method for producing ethene from natural gas comprises:
(1) Adopting a resonant cavity-type groove guide microwave chemical plant with working frequency within 0.3-22GHz, wherein the microwave source can adopt continuous wave or pulsed wave;
(2) Allowing the resonant cavity-type groove guide microwave chemical plant to be in resonant state, and allowing the reactor to be in vacuum state;
(3) Selecting hydrogen gas as auxiliary gas;
(4) Regulating pressures of feed natural gas and auxiliary hydrogen gas to 1-20 atm, respectively introducing them into the reactor via different flow meters for metering flow rates of the different gases;
(5) Adopting feed natural gas and auxiliary hydrogen gas flow rate ratio, i.e. natural gas: hydrogen gas, at 50:1-1:20;
(6) Mixing the feed natural gas and the auxiliary hydrogen gas in a gas mixture cabinet, and introducing into quartz reactor (41) of the resonant cavity-type groove guide microwave chemical plant via the feed gas inlet tube (46) and the upper end cover (42);
(7) Regulating the total pressure of the mixed gas in the quartz reactor (41) to 1x10-4 - 20 atm, and making the total pressure of the mixed gas in the quartz reactor (41) slightly lower than the pressure of the feed natural gas and the auxiliary hydrogen gas;
(8) Switching on the microwave source power supply, regulating microwave output power to several dozen watts to several hundred kilowatts according to auxiliary gas type, flow rate ratio, and gas mixture pressure, and allowing the gas mixture in the quartz reactor (41) to discharge so as to generate microwave plasma, wherein discharge condition can be learned from the Langmuir probe (44) and the cutoff waveguide;
(9) Then fine tuning microwave output power to obtain required product, wherein the required product ethene in liquid state can be collected in the condensation trap.

Procédé de production d'éthène à partir de gaz naturel par utilisation de l'installation chimique hyperfréquence à guide à rainure du type à cavité résonante selon la revendication 1, caractérisé en ce que le procédé pour la production d'éthène à partir de gaz naturel comprend :
(1) l'adoption d'une installation chimique hyperfréquence à guide à rainure du type à cavité résonante avec une fréquence de travail comprise entre 0,3 et 22 GHz, la source hyperfréquence pouvant adopter une onde continue ou une onde pulsée ;
(2) l'action de permettre à l'installation chimique hyperfréquence à guide à rainure du type à cavité résonante d'être dans l'état de résonance et l'action de permettre au réacteur d'être dans l'état vide ;
(3) la sélection du gaz hydrogène en tant que gaz auxiliaire ;
(4) la régulation des pressions du gaz naturel d'alimentation et du gaz hydrogène auxiliaire à 1-20 atm, leur introduction respective dans le réacteur via différents débitmètres pour mesurer les débits des différents gaz ;
(5) l'adoption d'un rapport de débit de gaz naturel d'alimentation et de gaz hydrogène auxiliaire, par ex. gaz naturel : gaz hydrogène, de 50:1-1:20;
(6) le mixage du gaz naturel d'alimentation et du gaz hydrogène auxiliaire dans une armoire de mélange de gaz, et l'introduction dans un réacteur à quartz (41) de l'installation chimique hyperfréquence à guide à rainure du type à cavité résonante via le tube d'entrée de gaz d'alimentation (46) et le couvercle d'extrémité supérieur (42) ;
(7) la régulation de la pression totale du gaz mélangé dans le réacteur à quartz (41) à 1x10-4 - 20 atm, et l'action d'amener la pression totale du gaz mélangé dans le réacteur à quartz (41) à une valeur légèrement inférieure à la pression du gaz naturel d'alimentation et du gaz hydrogène auxiliaire ;
(8) la mise en circuit de l'alimentation électrique de la source hyperfréquence, la régulation de la puissance de sortie hyperfréquence entre plusieurs douzaines de watts et plusieurs centaines de kilowatts selon le type de gaz auxiliaire, le rapport de débit, et la pression de mélange de gaz, et l'action de laisser le mélange de gaz dans le réacteur à quartz (41) se décharger de façon à générer le plasma hyperfréquence, l'état de la décharge pouvant être défini à partir de la sonde de Langmuir (45) et du guide d'ondes évanescent.
(9) Ensuite, le réglage fin de la puissance de sortie hyperfréquence pour obtenir le produit requis, le produit requis éthène dans l'état liquide pouvant être collecté dans le collecteur de condensation.
